article.headline: Kansas State 60, Denver 56
article.story: MANHATTAN, Kan. (AP) -- For the second time in as many games, Kansas State had to come from behind after a sluggish start for a win. Jeremiah Massey scored 15 points and Kansas State withstood a late Denver rally for a 60-56 victory Wednesday night. But that came after Kansas State (2-0) shot just 10-for-31 in the first half and allowed the Pioneers to lead most of the way. "I sit there during games and we're just having a hard time scoring," Kansas State coach Jim Wooldridge said. "It's a tough way to play basketball." The Wildcats were also 1-for-7 from 3-point range and shot 68 percent from the free throw line. "The intensity was just a little flat," Kansas State guard Clent Stewart said. "We're not ready to play." Denver center Yemi Nicholson had 10 of the Pioneer's 22 first-half points, but Kansas State was able to muscle its way to a 25-22 halftime lead in spite of its poor shooting. "We thought their physical play as a team had a lot to do with the outcome of the game," Denver coach Terry Caroll said. "We haven't seen physical guys like that." Despite the physical post game, Nicholson finished with career-highs of 27 points and 18 rebounds and had nearly as many field goals (12) as the rest of the team (13). "We didn't support the post and we left him isolated," Wooldridge said. "He was their go-to guy tonight." Kansas State missed its first six shots of the second half and Denver (1-1) used a 9-2 run to build a 31-27 lead. But two baskets by Massey, who had missed his first seven field goals, kept the Wildcats within range. Trailing 42-38 midway through the second half, the Wildcats went on a 17-4 run of their own to take a 55-46 lead with 2:50 to go. Lance Harris knocked down Kansas State's only 3-pointer to spark the run, and Fred Peete, who was just 1-for-7 at the time, hit three jump shots to pull the Wildcats ahead. "If I stop shooting, I let my team down," said Peete, who finished with 10 points. "At first I wasn't hitting, but I knew my team needed me. We needed baskets down the stretch." Kansas State struggled from the free-throw line in the final minutes, allowing Denver to close within two. But Massey stepped to the line and calmly sank two free throws with six seconds left to seal the win. "We are definitely disappointed," Caroll said. "We thought we had an opportunity to come in here and win the game. It just didn't work out."
